&gt;     In the past couple of weeks I have p=
osted (in the Files section) several poems transcribed into Senior Quikscri=
pt.  In transcribing them, I have used a couple of minor modifications/addi=
tions to Senior that I want to discuss here, and argue for their merits.  (=
These changes don&#39;t apply to Junior Quikscript because they are related to =
cursive writing and avoidance of penlifts in Senior).
&gt;
&gt;     The most comm=
only used modification relates to Letter 24, the symbol for the &quot;L&quot; sound. =
 Consider how to write the word &quot;flight&quot; in Senior using the regular letter=
 L:  a letter &quot;F&quot;, penlift, a letter &quot;L&quot;, penlift, a Letter 31 (&quot;my&quot;), and =
the final &quot;T&quot;.  Penlifts galore!  Now imagine an additional form for the le=
tter &quot;L&quot; which is formed by reflecting the original &quot;L&quot; horizontally so tha=
t the new form starts on the upper parallel and ends on the lower parallel =
instead of vice versa like the original &quot;L&quot;.  Now, using this alternate &quot;L&quot;=
, writing &quot;flight&quot; becomes:  a letter &quot;F&quot;, NO penlift, an alternate letter =
&quot;L&quot;, NO penlift, a Letter 31 (&quot;my&quot;), and the final &quot;T&quot;.  As with the altern=
ate letter &quot;N&quot; which can be &quot;upside down&quot; or right-side up, the alternate &quot;=
L&quot; would be called into service only when needed for ease of connected, pen=
lift-avoiding writing.  I don&#39;t think this &quot;new&quot; letter can be confused wit=
h any existing letter forms.  It&#39;s easily-recognizable as a &quot;backwards&quot; L.
=
&gt;
&gt;     Another less-often needed similar addition would allow the Letter 2=
1 (&quot;NG&quot;) to be written both right-side up and &quot;upside down&quot;, like its cousi=
n the letter &quot;N&quot;, useful in avoiding a penlift in writing the word &quot;leasing=
&quot;, since it would consist of an &quot;L&quot;, a Letter 27 (&quot;even&quot;) which ends on the=
 writing line so the following letter &quot;S&quot; would be written from bottom to t=
op (avoiding a penlift after the Letter 27), and now the pen is at tall-let=
ter height and the final Letter 21 needs to be written (the vowel Letter 26=
 being elided, as discussed on the bottom of page 18 of the Manual).....req=
uiring a big penlift to come down to the writing line to begin the final le=
tter.  But if Letter 21 (&quot;NG&quot;) could be written &quot;upside down&quot;, no penlift w=
ould be required.  Again, it&#39;s hard to imagine how an &quot;upside down&quot; Letter =
21 would not easily and immediately be recognized as such.
&gt;
&gt;     Since av=
oiding penlifts is a high priority in Senior, it seems to me that these are=
 useful additions.
